<br />

<br />
On a more serious note, regarding addictiveness of cigarettes:
<br />
The chance for a perosn to quit smoking cigarettes successfully is around 10%, and it's 60%+ for heroin. Some studies suggest 90% for heroin but I wonder if that was "best possible case", I'd suspect so. While heroin has a huge physical hit, cigarette smoking has a terrible psychological lock because of the time and frequency of use, plus social acceptability.
<br />
I.E. taking say 20 a day for 5+ years ingrains the action with fags, where as heroin is perhaps 1 to 3 times per day.
<br />
The ability of cigarettes to cause addiction rapidly is based on, again partially social acceptance, but basically down to the fact inhaled nicotine is one of the fastest acting narcotics there is. Note until, hm 15 years ago? nicotine was the fastest acting poison known. If you were injected with a drop of pure nictoine you'd be dead in 1.5 seconds.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.bupa.co.uk/health_information/html/health_news/060803nicotine.html" target="_blank">http://www.bupa.co.uk/health_information/html/health_news/060803nicotine.html</a>
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In the DANDY study, the addictive effects of smoking on children aged 12 and 13 were investigated. The research, published in 2002 by Dr. Joseph DiFranza, showed that 40 per cent of those children who'd ever smoked (even just a puff) showed signs of addiction, while 53 per cent of those children who inhaled had signs of addiction. With children being more susceptible than adults, it's a worrying situation.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
