</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Latest annual figures show:
<br />
- Fires started by cigarettes kill more people than any other kind of fire - accounting for one third of all fatal fires in the home.
<br />
- On average, 140 deaths and over 1,800 injuries each year occur as a result of fires caused by smoking.
<br />
- The number of deaths caused by cigarette fires increased by 11% in the UK, or nearly 30% in England and Wales.
<br />
- You are almost 5 times more likely to die and twice as likely to be injured in a fire caused by a cigarette than you are with other fires.
<br />
- The tip of a lit cigarette can reach a temperature of around 780º centigrade.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
There you go, 140 deaths per year, 1,800 injuries, and this is a AFTER years of *forcing* companies to change the materials used in household furniture to be safer, plus fitting smoke alarms etc.
<br />
Most companies banned smoking in the workplaces due ot health and safety years ago, so that potentially huge source of danger has been cut (since you can get sacked/fined etc). And yes I have seen numbnuts smoking in petrol stations, around chemical storage, in dry grassland/parks etc... <img src="images/smiles/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt="Rolling Eyes" border="0" /> Alas we are but human (me included, hehe).
<br />

<br />
If you assume the USA has similar statistics but made worse by geographical size (longer for emergency service ot reach you)..hm 1,000 deaths per year or more?
<br />
And having been burned I can assure you it is *not* fun for the oens who were lucky to survive.
<br />
I bet fire is part of the psychological stimulation of cigs, but making nictoine an inhaled product rather than combusted would be a lot safer from the fire aspect at least.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Overall, smoking should be considered the same as heroin, ampehtamine or similar drug use. Oh I'm not calling for a ban, but they shoud only be purchasable by credit card (thus proving age etc), from restricted outlets.
<br />
Unlike a normal product, their *addictiveness*, health and safety hazards are NOT to be taken lightly. Folk should have the freedom to smoke till their hair fries if they want, but they cigarettes shouldnt be treated as merely a "harmless, normal product" and they shouldnt be allowed ot endanger others. That's why there's laws controlling the use of drugs and dangerous tools/vehicles and the like.
<br />

<br />
A candy bar may not be the best hting for you're health, but neither is it so addictive, lethal or as incendiary as ciggies <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" border="0" /><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=304331" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: red">REDORIOUS.....ARCHMAGE.....KARANA</span></span></a>
<br />
